@startuml fig-websocket-vs-polling
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title WebSocket vs HTTP Polling — Real-Time Notification Strategies

participant "Client" as C1 #FFE0B2
participant "Server" as S1 #C8E6C9

== HTTP Polling (repeated requests) ==

C1 -> S1 : GET /notifications
S1 --> C1 : 200 [] (empty)

...2 seconds later...

C1 -> S1 : GET /notifications
S1 --> C1 : 200 [] (empty)

...2 seconds later...

C1 -> S1 : GET /notifications
S1 -[#43A047]-> C1 : 200 [{msg: "new data"}]

note right of S1
  Many requests return empty.
  Latency = poll interval.
  High overhead per request.
end note

|||
== ═══════════════════════════════ ==
|||

participant "Client" as C2 #FFE0B2
participant "Server" as S2 #C8E6C9

== WebSocket (persistent connection) ==

C2 -> S2 : GET /ws Upgrade: websocket
S2 -[#43A047]-> C2 : 101 Switching Protocols

...server event occurs...

S2 -[#1565C0]-> C2 : {"type":"deliver","msg":"new data"}

...another event...

S2 -[#1565C0]-> C2 : {"type":"deliver","msg":"update"}

note right of S2
  Server pushes instantly.
  No wasted requests.
  Connection stays open.
end note

legend bottom
  Polling wastes bandwidth on empty responses.
  WebSocket provides true push with sub-second latency.
  Trade-off: WebSocket requires persistent connections
  that consume server resources and complicate load balancing.
endlegend
@enduml
